body:
Using the following IR input:
```
module {
  firrtl.circuit "ChipTop" {
    firrtl.module @ChipTop() {
      %c0_ui1 = firrtl.constant 0 : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
  }
}
```

Converting this to bytecode using `circt-as input.mlir -o input.mlirbc`, `circt-opt input.mlir -emit-bytecode -o input.mlirbc`, or `firtool -parse-only input.mlir -emit-bytecode -o input.mlirbc` produces bytecode that we cannot read back.

Additionally, the same bytecode cannot be read by recent (e.g., from our pinned LLVM) `mlir-opt --allow-unregistered-dialect` which suggests this may be an upstream issue.

The same bytecode /can/ be read by our 1.40.0 tools, including the mlir-opt from that time.
Bytecode produced similarly using above methods using 1.40.0 tools is not identical but cannot be read using our tools or recent mlir-opt.  This may suggest this is a bug in bytecode reading introduced since then (?).

When failing to read the bytecode, no diagnostic is produced or assertion encountered, the tools simply exit immediately with error code 1 ("immediately" is more obvious on the non-reduced input I first observed this with).

Here's a copy of the bytecode that was generated using `circt-as` and behaves as described (can't be read by our tools or recent mlir-opt AFAICT): [bytecode-test.tar.gz](https://github.com/llvm/circt/files/11466526/bytecode-test.tar.gz)
